-- 
South African Stocks Decline; Anglo Platinum, Impaala Slide as Metal Drops

-- B y   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 
2011-05-03T15:48:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-03/south-african-stocks-decline-anglo-platinum-impala-slide-as-metal-drops.html
The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index
fell 510.40, or 1.6 percent, to 32,325.83 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg, the lowest since April 19.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , Africa’s biggest gold
miner, slipped 10.78 rand, or 3.2 percent, to 322 rand, the
weakest since March 29. Gold fell for the first day in five,
slipping as much as 2.4 percent.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , the
continent’s second-biggest producer of the metal, slipping 4.17
rand, or 3.6 percent, to 113.11 rand, the lowest since March 22.  ArcelorMittal South Africa Ltd. (ACL)  , a unit of the
world’s biggest steelmaker, declined 2.79 rand, or 3.1 percent,
to 87.01 rand, the biggest drop in two weeks. The company will
lift prices on a “small proportion” of speciality long-steel
products by 4.5 percent from June, it said in an e-mailed
response to a query today.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s biggest mining
company, dropped 3.70 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 270.80 rand, a
fourth day of decreases. Copper fell for a fourth day in London
on revived concern demand may weaken after figures showed slower
growth in manufacturing in China, the world’s largest consumer
of the metal.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , a diversified miner that makes
up 11 percent of the index, retreated 7.45 rand, or 2.2 percent,
to 338.05 rand, the lowest in more than two weeks.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd. (IMP)  , the world’s second-
largest platinum producer, retreated 7.76 rand, or 3.8 percent,
to 197.27 rand, the biggest drop since April 18. Platinum
declined as much as 1.4 percent to $1,851 an ounce.  Anglo Platinum Ltd. (AMS)  , the world’s biggest producer
of the metal, fell 19.01 rand, or 2.9 percent, to 647.99 rand,
snapping two days of gains.  Mr Price Group Ltd. (MPC)   advanced 50 cents, or 0.7
percent, to 67.70 rand. The clothing retailer said per-share
earnings probably rose between 48 percent and 53 percent in the
53 weeks that ended April 2 compared with the year-ago period.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the biggest producer of oil from coal,
fell 10.48 rand, or 2.8 percent, to 368.52 rand, the biggest
decrease in two weeks. Oil dropped for a second day in New York
on signs growth in the  U.S. economy  may slow.  To contact the reporter on this story:
